It can feel weird to post a photo & proclaim “I love this about me” or “I look good”.

There’s kind of an ick factor associated with self love, especially when it comes to physical traits.

But that’s the thing, it’s 100% ok. It’s more than ok, it’s awesome to love things both internal & external about yourself. Especially if it’s from a point of self love as opposed to conceit.

I see this all the time. On my client intake form, I ask what assets they love/want to play up & what they don’t love. Almost all of my clients leave the first section blank but then list a gazillion parts they want to play down.

Or the friends I was with after the IG live that said “oh I can’t name 3 physical things, but I could name internal stuff“ or “dang, I wish I appreciated the body I had 10/20 years ago, when I also didn’t like how I looked.”

That’s the essence of this challenge: to look at ourselves with loving eyes. The mere act of naming 3 things you love then posting them takes courage & will have positive effects.

What are my 3?

1️⃣My eyes. They’re getting more wrinkled, but it means I’m smiling. They’re the color of my grandpa’s eyes. When I want to feel strong, I wear turquoise blue because it brings out my eyes. It’s my armor to conquer the day. That’s why I love clothes, they can help one feel confident, even if the feeling isn’t there yet.

2️⃣My hair. When it’s freshly coiffed I feel like I can take on the world. When I was young, I wanted thin, stick straight hair like the other girls in my class. Now, I’m grateful for the mane I have.

3️⃣In this photo I’m showing my legs. I rarely do. They’re not my fav asset. I’m more comfortable in long dresses or pants. But in this pic I like them! Maybe it’s because I’m wearing my power color. Maybe it’s because the shorts hit at the right point. Or maybe it is because I have a heel on, elongating my legs.

I love that clothes have the ability to create balance & proportion where it might not naturally occur. Clothing is the ultimate optical illusion. If you know how to use it to your advantage, that instills confidence.

Thank you for joining this challenge & sharing your photos. I can’t wait to see them! #twcxsys

Stylists Tips for Buying and Wearing a Graphic Tee:

✨MAKE IT MEANINGFUL

Wear a tee that means something to you. Even if you bought it at Walmart, make sure it aligns with you - your taste in music, your humor, your political views.

✨FIT, FIT, FIT

Make sure the tee fits you. I personally like tee’s that have a bit of drape (aka softer fabric). But if you like tight tees then your graphic should fit that way too.

✨IT’S A TOOL

Think of your graphic tee as a tool that can turn up and down the volume of an outfit. The same way I talked a few weeks ago about the topper continuum, and how a topper can be used as a tool. So too can a graphic tee be used to take a dressier outfit and take it down a notch.

Blue, cobalt blue to be exact, is the other color, in addition to magenta that feels fresh right now. And the best part of it is that cobalt blue literally LOOKS GOOD ON EVERYONE.

Here are a few reasons that this is such a great color:

💙 Cobalt is considered a clean blue - which means it is neither warm or cool, therefore rendering it attractive on everyone!

💙 As blues go, cobalt is one that walks the fine line - it makes a statement but is not too brash, so it’s great for those that are color shy.

💙 Cobalt literally works with almost every other color. Black, navy, camel, grey, white, orange, green and all other shades of blue as well.

💙 From a color psychology perspective, blue symbolizes trust, truth, tranquility, cleanliness and contentment.

💙 Blue is associated with beauty in nature - think blue skies, and the blue of the sea…and because of this, there is a positive association.
